{"title_page": "Maria Dahl", "text_new": "{{short description|German zoologist}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Maria Johanna Dahl\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = Maria Johanna Grosset\n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Maria Dahl (nee Grosset).jpg\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth date |1872|07|26}}\n| birth_place       = Boromlya, Poltava region, Russian Empire\n| death_date        = {{death date and age |1972|01|06 |1872|07|26}}\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| home_town         = \n| other_names       = \n| siglum            = \n| pronounce         = \n| citizenship       = Germany\n| nationality       = \n| fields            = zoology, arachnology, carcinology\n| workplaces        = \n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = \n| known_for         = ''Die Tierwelt Deutschland''\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = [[Friedrich Dahl]]\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n}}\n'''Maria Johanna Dahl,''' n\u00e9e '''Grosset''' (26 July, 1872, Boromlya, Poltava Region \u2013 6 January 1972) was a Ukrainian-born German zoologist, [[Arachnology|arachnologist]], and [[Carcinology|carcinologist]]. Along with her husband, [[Friedrich Dahl]], she was a co-author and editor of the zoological series ''Die Tierwelt Deutschland,'' published between 1925 and 1968.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Life ==\nMaria Johanna Grosset was born on 26 July 1872 in Boromlya, Russian Empire (currently in [[Poltava Oblast|Poltava Region]], Ukraine).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sears|first=M.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jUrTBwAAQBAJ|title=Oceanography: The Past: Proceedings of the Third International Congress on the History of Oceanography, held September 22-26, 1980 at the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Woods Hole, Massachusetts, USA on the occasion of the Fiftieth Anniversary of the founding of the Institution|last2=Merriman|first2=D.|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-1-4613-8090-0|location=|pages=469|language=en}}</ref> She was an honor graduate from the Girls Gymnasium in [[Kharkiv]].<ref name=\":3\" />  In 1889, Grosset became a teacher of culture.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title=GIA - Grupo Ib\u00e9rico de Aracnologia|url=http://sea-entomologia.org/gia/biografia_dahl_m.html|website=sea-entomologia.org|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1890, Grosset immigrated with her family to Kiel, Germany, where she attended a vocational school.<ref name=\":1\" /> She planned to study medicine, however, at that time only men could attend medical schools in Germany.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1891, Groset had to retake the exams, as her Russian diploma was not recognized in Germany.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 19 June 1899 Grosset married Professor Friedrich Dahl.<ref name=\":1\" /> The couple had four children.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Apple|first=Rima D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wl0ZWkaTtKIC|title=Science in Print: Essays on the History of Science and the Culture of Print|last2=Downey|first2=Gregory J.|last3=Vaughn|first3=Stephen L.|date=2012-09-25|publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres|year=|isbn=978-0-299-28613-2|location=|pages=77|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDue to Friedrich Dahl's health problems, the Dahl family moved to [[Greifswald]] where Dahl continued to live after her husband's death in 1929.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMaria Dahl died on 6 January 1972 at the age of 99.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Sears|first=M.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jUrTBwAAQBAJ|title=Oceanography: The Past: Proceedings of the Third International Congress on the History of Oceanography, held September 22-26, 1980 at the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Woods Hole, Massachusetts, USA on the occasion of the Fiftieth Anniversary of the founding of the Institution|last2=Merriman|first2=D.|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-1-4613-8090-0|location=|pages=471|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1892 to 1899 Dahl was employed as an assistant to [[Karl Brandt (zoologist)|Karl Brandt]] at Zoological institute in Kiel where she was working with the collections from the 1889-90 Plankton-Expedition.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Truesdale|first=Frank|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oMQTwzwQXakC|title=History of Carcinology|date=1993-06-01|publisher=CRC Press|year=|isbn=978-90-5410-137-6|location=|pages=177|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the two decades after getting married in 1899, Dahl was mainly occupied by the birth and education of her four children.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, around 1907 her husband, Friedrich Dahl, encouraged her to pursue the work he had started on the corycacid [[Copepod|copepods]] of the Plankton-Expedition.<ref name=\":3\" /> Working at home, by 1912 Dahl had completed a monograph of excellence, planned as one part of the series.<ref name=\":2\" /> In the foreword to her analysis of the copepod genus ''[[Corycacinen]]'', Dahl apologized for not having a PhD in zoology and for taking too long to complete the task.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAfter [[World War I]] Dahl was engaged in [[arachnid]] research along with her husband.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1920, Dahl began her research at the [[Humboldt University of Berlin|University of Berlin]] and was occupied with it until 1925.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDahl's and her husband's joint research culminated in publishing ''Die Tierwelt Deutschlands'' in 1925.<ref name=\":3\" /> Friedrich Dahl was its founder and author of the first three volumes, while Maria co-authored the fifth volume and edited 15 volumes.<ref name=\":3\" />  A review in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' called ''Die Tierwelt Deutschlands'' \"a reference book necessary to every library of zoology\", noting that \"each species is given an excellent and well-illustrated systematic description\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Die Tierwelt Deutschlands und der angrenzenden Meeresteile nach ihren Merkmalen und nach ihrer Lebensweise|journal=Nature|volume=134|issue=3391|year=1934|pages=648\u2013648|issn=0028-0836|doi=10.1038/134648b0}}</ref> After Friedrich Dahl\u2019s death in 1929, Dahl continued editing ''Die Tierwelt Deutschlands'' until 1968.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDahl also published several works on spiders and finished editing her husband\u2019s book on [[Melanesia]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Beolens|first=Bo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_3QDwAAQBAJ|title=The Eponym Dictionary of Birds|last2=Watkins|first2=Michael|last3=Grayson|first3=Michael|date=2020-03-19|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-4729-8269-8|location=|pages=140|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== List of works<ref name=\":1\" />==\n\n* 1926 - Dahl (M.) (Maria), ''Spinentiere\u00a0 oder Arachnoidea. I.Spring-spinnen (Salticidae)''. Tierw. Deuts., 1926, pp.1-55, 159 fig.\n* 1927 - Dahl (M.), vide DAHL (F.) & Maria DAHL, 1927.\n* 1928 - Dahl (M.), ''Einige Lebendbeobachtungen an Argiope lobata (Arachneae, Argiopidae)''. Zool. Anz., 75 (3-4), pp.79-85\n* 1928 - Dahl (M.), ''Spinnen (Araneae) von Nowaja-Semlja''. Norsk. Vid. Akard. Oslo, 1928, pp.1-37.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=America|first=Arctic Institute of North|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=05oZAAAAMAAJ&|title=Arctic Bibliography|date=1953|publisher=Department of Defense|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=550|language=en}}</ref>\n*1931 - Dahl (M.), ''Spinnentiere oder Arachnoidea. VI. 24 Familie: Agelenidae''. Tierw. Deuts., 1931, pp.1-46, 76 fig.\n*1933 - Dahl (M.), ''Spinnen (Araneae). in The Norwegian North Polar Expedition with the Maud 1918-1925'', Scientific Results, 5 (16), pp.3-4.<ref name=\":5\" />\n*1935 - Dahl (M.), ''Zur Kenntnis der Spinnentiere Schlesiens. A. Araneae und Opiliones''. Sitz-ber. Ges naturf. Freu. Berlin, 1935, pp.337-353.\n*1937 - Dahl (M.), ''Spinnentiere oder Arachnoidea. VIII. 19 Familie: Hahniidae''. Tierw. Deuts., 1937, pp.100-114, 33 fig.\n*1937 - Dahl (M.), ''Spinnentiere oder Arachnoidea. VIII. 20 Familie: Argyronetidae''. Tierw. Deuts., 1937, pp.115-118, fig.34-38.\n*1938 - Dahl (M.), ''Zur Verbreitung der Gattung Porrhomma in deutschen H\u00f6hlen, Stollen, Bergwerten und Kellern und deren freilebenden Arten''. Mitt. H\u00f6hl. u. Karstjorsch., 1938, pp.122 132, 9 fig.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:German women scientists]]\n[[Category:German arachnologists]]\n\n[[Category:19th-century women scientists]]\n\n[[Category:19th-century German zoologists]]\n[[Category:German women scientists]]\n[[Category:German arachnologists]]\n[[Category:German carcinologists]]\n[[Category:19th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:People of Ukrainian descent]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dahl, Maria}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German zoologist}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Maria Johanna Dahl\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = Maria Johanna Grosset\n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Maria Dahl (nee Grosset).jpg\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth date |1872|07|26}}\n| birth_place       = Boromlya, Poltava region, Russian Empire\n| death_date        = {{death date and age |1972|01|06 |1872|07|26}}\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| home_town         = \n| other_names       = \n| siglum            = \n| pronounce         = \n| citizenship       = Germany\n| nationality       = \n| fields            = zool